# 1. Linux Boot Process

The Linux boot process is the sequence of steps performed when a Linux system starts.

## Boot Sequence

```text
Power On
    ↓
BIOS / UEFI
    ↓
Boot Loader (GRUB/LILO)
    ↓
Linux Kernel (vmlinuz)
    ↓
initrd / initramfs
    ↓
systemd (PID 1)
    ↓
System Services
    ↓
Login Screen / Shell
```

---

## BIOS / UEFI

- BIOS (Basic Input Output System) initializes the hardware.
- UEFI is the modern replacement for BIOS.
- Performs POST (Power-On Self-Test).
- Searches for a bootable device.

### Interview Point

- BIOS/UEFI initializes hardware before the operating system starts.

---

## Boot Loader

A boot loader loads the Linux kernel into memory.

Examples:

- GRUB (Most commonly used)
- LILO (Older boot loader)

Responsibilities:

- Displays the boot menu.
- Allows selecting an operating system.
- Loads the Linux kernel.

---

## Linux Kernel

Kernel file:

```text
vmlinuz
```

Responsibilities:

- Initializes CPU and memory.
- Detects hardware.
- Loads device drivers.
- Mounts the root filesystem.
- Starts the first process (`systemd`).

---

## initrd / initramfs

Temporary root filesystem loaded into RAM.

Purpose:

- Loads required drivers.
- Mounts the real root filesystem.
- Hands control to the Linux kernel.

---

## systemd

`systemd` is the first userspace process.

Process ID:

```text
PID = 1
```

Responsibilities:

- Starts services.
- Manages processes.
- Handles system startup.
- Controls shutdown and reboot.

Useful commands:

```bash
systemctl status
systemctl start <service_name>
systemctl stop <service_name>
systemctl restart <service_name>
systemctl enable <service_name>
systemctl disable <service_name>
```

---

## Runlevels & Targets

### Legacy Runlevels

| Runlevel | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| 0 | Shutdown |
| 1 | Single User Mode |
| 3 | Multi User Mode |
| 5 | Graphical Mode |
| 6 | Reboot |

### Systemd Targets

| Runlevel | Target |
|----------|--------|
| 0 | poweroff.target |
| 1 | rescue.target |
| 3 | multi-user.target |
| 5 | graphical.target |
| 6 | reboot.target |

Check default target:

```bash
systemctl get-default
```

---

## Shutdown Commands

```bash
shutdown now
shutdown -r now
shutdown -h now
reboot
poweroff
halt
```

