# 2. System Logging

Linux records system and application events in log files.

Logs help administrators troubleshoot problems and monitor system health.

---

## Common Log Files

```text
/var/log/
/var/log/syslog
/var/log/messages
/var/log/auth.log
/var/log/dmesg
```

---

## dmesg

Displays kernel boot messages.

Commands:

```bash
dmesg
dmesg | less
dmesg | grep error
```

Used for:

- Hardware detection
- Boot issues
- Driver errors
- USB detection
- Disk failures

---

## Syslog

Syslog is the standard Linux logging system.

It collects logs from:

- Kernel
- Applications
- Services
- System processes

---

## Syslog Facilities

Facilities identify where the log originated.

Examples:

- auth
- mail
- cron
- daemon
- kern
- local0 - local7

---

## Syslog Severity Levels

| Level | Meaning |
|--------|----------|
| 0 | Emergency |
| 1 | Alert |
| 2 | Critical |
| 3 | Error |
| 4 | Warning |
| 5 | Notice |
| 6 | Information |
| 7 | Debug |

Easy way to remember:

```text
Emergency → Debug
Highest Severity → Lowest Severity
```

---

## Logger Command

Generate your own log message.

```bash
logger "Backup completed successfully"
```

Useful in Bash scripts and automation.

---

## Log Rotation

Linux uses **logrotate** to manage log files.

Purpose:

- Prevent disk from filling up.
- Compress old log files.
- Delete outdated logs.
- Create new log files automatically.

Command:

```bash
logrotate
```

---

# DevOps / SRE Notes

## Why the Boot Process Matters

Understanding the Linux boot process helps troubleshoot:

- Server not booting
- Kernel panic
- GRUB failures
- Failed services after reboot

---

## Why Logs Matter

Logs are the first place to investigate when:

- Applications crash
- Services fail
- Authentication issues
- Docker containers stop
- Kubernetes Pods fail

---

## Why systemctl Matters

Most modern Linux servers use `systemd`.

Common commands:

```bash
systemctl status nginx
systemctl restart nginx
systemctl enable nginx
journalctl -u nginx
```

These commands are frequently used in production environments.

---

## Why dmesg Matters

Use `dmesg` to troubleshoot:

- Hardware failures
- Memory errors
- USB detection issues
- Disk failures
- Driver loading problems

---

# Interview Points

- `systemd` is the first userspace process (PID 1).
- GRUB is the most common Linux boot loader.
- `dmesg` displays kernel boot messages.
- System logs are stored under `/var/log`.
- `logger` creates custom log messages.
- `logrotate` prevents log files from consuming all disk space.
- Logs are one of the first things checked during production incidents.

